                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 8.295,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Sotomayor has our first signed opinion in this term in case 13-517, Warger v. Shauers."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 8.295,
                        "stop": 272.744,
                        "byte_start": 0,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15131,
                            "name": "Sonia Sotomayor",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/sonia_sotomayor",
                            "last_name": "Sotomayor",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2776,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 1249707600,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": null,
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2776"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32685,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 50379,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/sonia_sotomayor_0.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 2293,
                            "identifier": "sonia_sotomayor"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 8.295,
                                "stop": 18.34,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This case comes to us from the Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit and concerns the interpretation of Federal Rule of Evidence 606 (b)."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 18.34,
                                "stop": 29.881,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "That rule provides that certain juror testimony regarding what occurred in a jury room is inadmissible during an inquiry into the validity of the verdict."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 29.881,
                                "stop": 45.727,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The question presented is whether this rule precludes the use of juror deliberations evidence during a proceeding in which a party seeks a new trial on the ground that a juror had lied during jury selection."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 45.727,
                                "stop": 53.527,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Petitioner was injured when while riding a motorcycle, he was struck by a truck driven by the respondent."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 53.527,
                                "stop": 61.96,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "He sued for negligence in Federal District Court but the jury returned a verdict for respondent."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 61.96,
                                "stop": 70.456,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "After trial, one of the jurors approached petitioner\u0027s counsel to voice concerns about the conduct of another juror."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 70.456,
                                "stop": 83.824,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The complaining juror signed an affidavit stating that during deliberations this other juror had discussed the motor vehicle collision in which her daughter was at fault and a man had died."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 83.824,
                                "stop": 92.561,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "According to the affidavit the juror had related that if her daughter had been sued it would have ruined her life."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 92.561,
                                "stop": 95.566,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Petitioner moved the court for a new trial."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 95.566,
                                "stop": 112.298,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "He contended that this affidavit demonstrated that the juror who discussed her daughter\u0027s accident had lied when during jury selection she affirmed that she would be fair and impartial and would be able to award damages in this sort of case."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 112.298,
                                "stop": 115.44,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The District Court refused to grant a new trial."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 115.44,
                                "stop": 124.859,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "It concluded that the only evidence that would support petitioner\u0027s motion, the affidavit, was barred by Federal Rule of Evidence 606 (b)."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 124.859,
                                "stop": 134.39,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The Eighth Circuit affirmed, rejecting petitioner\u0027s argument that Rule 606 (b) was inapplicable in these circumstances."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 134.39,
                                "stop": 150.35,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "We affirm, as the Eighth Circuit correctly concluded Rule 606 (b) is fully applicable during a proceeding in which a party seeks a new trial on the ground that a juror lied during voir dire."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 150.35,
                                "stop": 166.503,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The rule by its terms applies during an inquiry into the validity of a verdict and a post verdict motion for a new trial on the ground of voir dire dishonesty plainly requires such an inquiry."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 166.503,
                                "stop": 187.712,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "As we held in McDonough Power Equipment v. Greenwood, if a party shows that a juror was dishonest during voir dire and an honest response would have provided a valid basis to challenge that juror for cause the verdict must be invalidated."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 187.712,
                                "stop": 214.241,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Moreover Congress based Rule 606 (b) on the restrictive version of the common-law rule, precluding jurors from impeaching their own verdicts and the vast majorities of courts applying this rule had held that juror deliberations evidence was inadmissible even if used to support a new trial motion predicated on the assertion that a juror lied prior to trial."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 214.241,
                                "stop": 229.357,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "We also conclude that the juror affidavit here fell outside Rule 606 (b) (2)\u0027s exception for evidence as to whether extraneous prejudicial information was improperly brought to the juror\u0027s attention."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 229.357,
                                "stop": 238.09,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This exception generally enables parties to show that external information related to the case was introduced into the jury room."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 238.09,
                                "stop": 264.542,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Here petitioner argues that because the juror\u0027s alleged lies would, if revealed, have led her to be excluded from the jury anything she said in the jury room was necessarily extraneous, but this reading of the extraneous information exception would swallow much of the rest of Rule 606 (b) and we have implicitly rejected it before."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 264.542,
                                "stop": 268.412,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The judgment of the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals is therefore affirmed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 268.412,
                                "stop": 272.744,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This opinion is for a unanimous Court."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
